snippet.textDisplay: Is it bad to comment each day? One thing yoga has taught me during my several, very inconsistent attempts is that dry skin=sliding. No matter the yoga mat, a towel, the carpet----slip! I'm giggling as I do knowing full well that my poses are far from perfect, but I am up off the couch and moving. This is also a great reminder to pamper myself a bit more with a pedicure tonight and some good lotion for my hands! Thank you, Adriene!

snippet.textDisplay:
HOME - day 5/30:
Today was my first day back in school after my Christmas break, and I haven’t been feeling or sleeping very well the past few days, so I was completely drained by the time I got home. This practise helped me breathe through my emotions and maybe even soften a little.💕 Also, side note: once again, today I was reminded just how incredibly Benji has mastered the art of pure ~chill~ 🧘🏼‍♀️, in stark contrast to my guinea pigs who jump around their cage like two acrobats and every once in a while just start shrieking with a volume you wouldn’t think their tiny bodies were capable of.😳 Like, baby girls, I get you need a snack, but mommy’s gotta do her yoga first, OK?😂

snippet.textDisplay: It's interesting how our mind works. In the beginning of the practice during a nice comfortable seat, I felt that I wanted to feel supported - for my to be able to lean on something, feel ground under my feet, got the picture in my head of me sitting with my back against the wall, my knees bent and feet on the ground (I never sit this way normally). My brain told me - no, you can't sit like that, that's nor even yoga. I hesitated for few moments, but then replied, of course it is, it's totally yoga, just to find myself transitioning into a different posture to find what feels good. Today's practice felt like a hug - thank you Adriene!

I usually try to mobilise every muscles to hit the poses. Not that the pose is that important to me, but I do try to get a work-out out of it. When you talked about working too much, it suddenly made so much sense.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm glad that this is a core part of this journey. My intention that I set for this practice is to be gentle with myself, to be compassionate. It's a struggle for me, but the reminder and the chance to practice it makes it easier. The thought of 'where am I tensing in my mind, where can I be gentle in my thoughts' is very helpful. I often feel like allowing myself to be present in the moment is the most strenuous task in yoga. But when I do achieve it, it is worthwhile. I still have a long way to go, but I'm learning to accept where I am on the path.

snippet.textDisplay: All five HOME practices have been wonderful so far, but today's was just BRILLIANT!  Finding the ease/grace in my practice has always taken more work for me than the activation bit.  Slowing down, finding the sukha both on and off the mat, and noticing areas where physically and mentally I am perhaps putting in too much effort - beautiful reminder!  (and a high-paw to my 9-week-old puppy for finding her own sukha and letting me complete the whole practice in one go - Bluey must be taking her cues from Benji ;o) )

snippet.textDisplay: I was diagnosed with Multiple Sclorosis in 2017 (age 26).. I could barely get out of the bed in the first year.  I decided to stop all medications and treat my disease naturally.. healthy eating (eliminating all inflammatory foods), exercise/yoga and meditation... Your videos have made such a difference in my life Adrienne! I just want to thank you for all the work you put into these. I have never felt better - I am feeling stronger everyday and more confident. I think you are such a sweet person to do this for people. I have been following your yoga videos consistently every day for over 4 months now and I am so grateful for you and how you have helped me in my journey. I just wanted to say thank you, so so much. ❤️

snippet.textDisplay: Usually I do my YWA sesh at dawn when the house is dark and I'm alone while the sun rises and coffee brews. Needless to say it's THE BEST! way to start each day. But today I woke up late and was doing yoga in the the middle of the living room while husband was scurrying to get to work, kids waking up and humming songs working on art projects... it was a bit of comedy to try to be still and quiet and not react to the buzz. But I really enjoyed my experience and am feeling stoked from it so here I am, making my first comment on a YWA vid. So much thanks to the whole YWA crew and everyone who comes together to make all of this possible. Make a beautiful day Every Body!

snippet.textDisplay: I am so grateful for today's practice. Last Summer I suffered two concussions and my brain is still in the process of reconstructing itself. This is called post-concussion syndrome. Basically my brain becomes overloaded (neuro fatigue) and I become nauseous and confused. Yesterday I overextended myself and as much as I wanted to complete day 4 my body would not let me. I was hopeful that a good night's rest would remove most of my symptoms but sadly my brain is not done resting yet from yesterday. However I know that exercises wonderful for the brain and I wanted to complete today's session anyway. Hearing you say that the practice doesn't have to be perfect, that you just need to show up, meant everything to me. I wanted to let you know an offer my thanks. My intention is to become stronger and I look forward to the end of my 30 days here and beyond.
